The start symbol S has only the rule

  S → NT41 NT1

NT1 is a terminal‐producing nonterminal and so generates exactly one terminal. NT41 has no direct terminal production (only binary productions), so it must generate at least two terminals. Hence any S‐derivation produces at least three terminals, never exactly two. The string “t32 t30” is of length 2, so it cannot be generated. 

No

We note the start‐rule is  
 S → NT41 NT1  

In a CNF derivation of a 3‐symbol string w1w2w3, S → XY means X must generate w1w2 and Y must generate w3. Here Y=NT1 must generate the 3rd symbol “t0”. But NT1→“t4” is its only terminal rule, so NT1 cannot yield “t0”. Hence there is no way to derive “t4 t18 t0” from S.  

No

After attempting all splits of the 4‐token string under the only production S → NT41 NT1, none of NT41/NT1 (or their decompositions) can yield the required substrings “t34 t42”, “t42 t36 t26”, etc.  Hence the string is not in the language.  
No

After running a CYK‐style check (noting the only S production is S→NT41 NT1, NT1→'t4', and that NT41 cannot derive the length‑3 prefix t0 t32 t7), the string t0 t32 t7 t4 is not generated.  
No

To generate a 4‐token string S must split as S→NT41 NT1, with NT41 covering the first 3 tokens and NT1 the last one.  But NT1 has no rule producing “t38,” so it cannot yield the final token.  Hence the string cannot be generated.  
No

After building the usual CYK chart for the five‐token string (t11 t41 t38 t4 t4), one sees that no span of the first four tokens ever yields NT41, so there is no way to split the string to satisfy S→NT41 NT1 (and in fact NT41 never covers the first four tokens in the chart). Hence the start symbol S cannot derive the entire string. 

No

  S → NT41 NT1

the only way NT1 can terminate is via

  NT1 → 't4'

– NT1 has no binary (NT→NT NT) expansions.  Hence any string in L(G) must end in t4.  Our target ends in t19, so it cannot be generated.

No

After running a CYK‐style check you find that the only way to derive the full 5‐token string from S is via the single rule

  S → NT41 NT1

so NT41 would have to cover the first four tokens and NT1 the last one. We do have NT1 ⇒ t11, but there is no way for NT41 to derive the first four tokens t0 t31 t42 t10 (its only binary rule is NT41 → NT64 NT31, and neither side can cover the required spans). Hence the string is not generated.  
No

After attempting all ways to split the five terminals between NT41 and NT1 in the single rule S → NT41 NT1, none of the spans can be matched by NT41 (must start “t4 …”) and NT1 (must end “… t11”) under the huge collection of CNF productions. No valid derivation exists.

  NT41 → NT64 NT31

and NT64 only ever produces ‘t0’ as a terminal.  Therefore NT41 cannot start with ‘t41’, so no derivation matches the string.  Hence the answer is:

In particular NT41 never appears covering the left part and NT1 cannot cover the right part of the full span, so S cannot generate the string.

No sequence of binary rules lines up to cover “t0 t14 t14 t12 t5.”  Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.
